# Fluff Date: 2026-02-09 16:25:29
overview:<p>Developed in the early thirty-second century by Majesty Metals and Manufacturing on Canopus IV, the Agrotera traces its lineage to the Word of Blake's Phoenix Hawk variant. Majesty Metals advertises the fifty-ton design as a superior alternative to ammunition-dependent 'Mechs such as the Legionnaire and Shockwave, emphasizing its all-energy weapons complement for extended battlefield endurance.</p><p>Built on an Earthwerks PXH II reinforced endo steel chassis, the Agrotera features a Rawlings 300 XL engine matched with Rawlings 45 jump jets and a partial wing system for an impressive 240-meter jump envelope. Considerable firepower flexibility helps the Agrotera excel in a variety of roles, though it is most frequently deployed in support of lighter scout elements.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Agrotera's fully energy-based weapons complement gives it exceptional battlefield endurance and loitering capability, a quality greatly appreciated by quartermasters. The Ceres Arms Smasher ER PPC serves as the primary weapon, while a Diverse Optics 37V medium variable-speed pulse laser and Diverse Optics medium pulse laser provide flexible medium-range firepower. Twin Diverse Optics small pulse lasers round out the arsenal for close-range engagements. A Tek Tru-Trak targeting system with integrated TAG enables coordination with missile-equipped allies.</p><p>The partial wing system combined with standard jump jets provides outstanding mobility, allowing aggressive vertical maneuvers and rapid disengagement. First-time pilots frequently praise the Agrotera's comfortable and spacious cockpit, though qualifying times remain slightly longer than comparable 'Mechs due to the complexity of operating the variable-speed pulse lasers and partial wing simultaneously.</p><p>The primary limitation is heat management during sustained engagements, as the all-energy loadout generates significant thermal output. Extreme environmental conditions can further restrict firepower, forcing pilots to rely on disciplined fire selection rather than full salvos.</p>

deployment:<p>The base AGT-1A mounts a Ceres Arms Smasher ER PPC as its primary weapon, supported by a Diverse Optics 37V medium variable-speed pulse laser, a Diverse Optics medium pulse laser, and twin Diverse Optics small pulse lasers. The Rawlings 300 XL engine provides a top speed of 97 kilometers per hour, while the partial wing and jump jet combination enables 240-meter jumps. Durallex Light armor provides standard protection on the endo steel chassis. The Tek BattleCom communications system and Tek Tru-Trak targeting computer with integrated TAG complete the package, enabling the Agrotera to designate targets for allied missile formations while engaging independently.</p>

history:<p>The Agrotera entered production at Majesty Metals and Manufacturing on Canopus IV in approximately 3108, initially serving with Magistracy of Canopus forces. The First Magistracy Highlanders were among the earliest units to deploy the design, using Agroteras against bandit forces threatening Bethonolog. Outnumbered and outmassed against a lance of aging heavies, a pair of Agroteras relied on aggressive hit-and-run strikes and vertical maneuvers to pin the enemy until reinforcements arrived, ultimately destroying one bandit 'Mech and crippling two others.</p><p>The Capellan Confederation became a significant Agrotera operator, deploying the design during the 3144 invasion of Cumberland. In the Sarasota Flats engagement, mixed Agrotera and Yinghuchong lances inflicted significant casualties on Federated Suns forces over four days. Despite extreme heat hampering full firepower output, Capellan pilots exploited the 'Mech's mobility to isolate targets and concentrate fire before jumping clear. Frustrated FedSuns MechWarriors resorted to overheating alpha strikes while the Capellans methodically disabled five machines and captured two DropShips.</p><p>The Agrotera has influenced tactical doctrine within both the Magistracy Highlanders and the Capella War College, where instructors have developed specialized curricula for partial-wing tactics focused on mobility rather than aerial assault. The design continues to see increasing deployment as production at Canopus IV matures.</p>

